# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: materialized-view
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:materialized-view/database-index] A **database index** is a data structure that improves the speed of data retrieval operations on a database table at the cost of additional writes and storage space to maintain the index data structure.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Indexes are used to quickly locate data without having to search every row in a database table every time said table is accessed.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Indexes can be created using one or more columns of a database table, providing the basis for both rapid random lookups and efficient access of ordered records.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] An index is a copy of selected columns of data, from a table, that is designed to enable very efficient search.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] An index normally includes a "key" or direct link to the original row of data from which it was copied, to allow the complete row to be retrieved efficiently.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Some databases extend the power of indexing by letting developers create indexes on column values that have been transformed by functions or expressions.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] For example, an index could be created on `upper(last_name)`, which would only store the upper-case versions of the `last_name` field in the index.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Another option sometimes supported is the use of partial index, where index entries are created only for those records that satisfy some conditional expression.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] A further aspect of flexibility is to permit indexing on user-defined functions, as well as expressions formed from an assortment of built-in functions.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Most database software includes indexing technology that enables sub-linear time lookup to improve performance, as linear search is inefficient for large databases.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Suppose a database contains N data items and one must be retrieved based on the value of one of the fields.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] A simple implementation retrieves and examines each item according to the test.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] If there is only one matching item, this can stop when it finds that single item, but if there are multiple matches, it must test everything.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] This means that the number of operations in the average case is O(N) or linear time.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Since databases may contain many objects, and since lookup is a common operation, it is often desirable to improve performance.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] An index is any data structure that improves the performance of lookup.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] There are many different data structures used for this purpose.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] There are complex design trade-offs involving lookup performance, index size, and index-update performance.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Many index designs exhibit logarithmic (O(log(N))) lookup performance and in some applications it is possible to achieve flat (O(1)) performance.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Indexes are used to police database constraints, such as UNIQUE, EXCLUSION, PRIMARY KEY and FOREIGN KEY.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] An index may be declared as UNIQUE, which creates an implicit constraint on the underlying table.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Database systems usually implicitly create an index on a set of columns declared PRIMARY KEY, and some are capable of using an already-existing index to police this constraint.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Many database systems require that both referencing and referenced sets of columns in a FOREIGN KEY constraint are indexed, thus improving performance of inserts, updates and deletes to the tables participating in the constraint.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Some database systems support an EXCLUSION constraint that ensures that, for a newly inserted or updated record, a certain predicate holds for no other record.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] This can be used to implement a UNIQUE constraint (with equality predicate) or more complex constraints, like ensuring that no overlapping time ranges or no intersecting geometry objects would be stored in the table.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] An index supporting fast searching for records satisfying the predicate is required to police such a constraint.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] The data is present in arbitrary order, but the **logical ordering** is specified by the index.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] The data rows may be spread throughout the table regardless of the value of the indexed column or expression.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] The non-clustered index tree contains the index keys in sorted order, with the leaf level of the index containing the pointer to the record (page and the row number in the data page in page-organized engines; row offset in file-organized engines).
[src:materialized-view/database-index] There can be more than one non-clustered index on a database table.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Clustering alters the data block into a certain distinct order to match the index, resulting in the row data being stored in order.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Therefore, only one clustered index can be created on a given database table.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Clustered indexes can greatly increase overall speed of retrieval, but usually only where the data is accessed sequentially in the same or reverse order of the clustered index, or when a range of items is selected.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Since the physical records are in this sort order on disk, the next row item in the sequence is immediately before or after the last one, and so fewer data block reads are required.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] The primary feature of a clustered index is therefore the ordering of the physical data rows in accordance with the index blocks that point to them.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Some databases separate the data and index blocks into separate files, others put two completely different data blocks within the same physical file(s).
[src:materialized-view/database-index] When multiple databases and multiple tables are joined, it is called a **cluster** (not to be confused with clustered index described previously).
[src:materialized-view/database-index] The records for the tables sharing the value of a cluster key shall be stored together in the same or nearby data blocks.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] This may improve the joins of these tables on the cluster key, since the matching records are stored together and less I/O is required to locate them.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] The cluster configuration defines the data layout in the tables that are parts of the cluster.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] A cluster can be keyed with a B-tree index or a hash table.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] The data block where the table record is stored is defined by the value of the cluster key.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] The order that the index definition defines the columns in is important.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] It is possible to retrieve a set of row identifiers using only the first indexed column.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] However, it is not possible or efficient (on most databases) to retrieve the set of row identifiers using only the second or greater indexed column.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] For example, in a phone book organized by city first, then by last name, and then by first name, in a particular city, one can easily extract the list of all phone numbers.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] However, it would be very tedious to find all the phone numbers for a particular last name.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] One would have to look within each city's section for the entries with that last name.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Some databases can do this, others just won't use the index.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Then a sequential lookup checks the matching with `first_name`.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] So, to improve the performance, one must ensure that the index is created on the order of search columns.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Indexes are useful for many applications but come with some limitations.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Consider the following SQL statement: `SELECT first_name FROM people WHERE last_name = 'Smith';`.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] To process this statement without an index the database software must look at the last_name column on every row in the table (this is known as a full table scan).
[src:materialized-view/database-index] With an index the database simply follows the index data structure (typically a B-tree) until the Smith entry has been found; this is much less computationally expensive than a full table scan.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Consider this SQL statement: `SELECT email_address FROM customers WHERE email_address LIKE '%@wikipedia.org';`.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] This query would yield an email address for every customer whose email address ends with "@wikipedia.org", but even if the email_address column has been indexed the database must perform a full index scan.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] This is because the index is built with the assumption that words go from left to right.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] With a wildcard at the beginning of the search-term, the database software is unable to use the underlying index data structure (in other words, the WHERE-clause is *not sargable*).
[src:materialized-view/database-index] This problem can be solved through the addition of another index created on `reverse(email_address)` and a SQL query like this: `SELECT email_address FROM customers WHERE reverse(email_address) LIKE reverse('%@wikipedia.org');`.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] This puts the wild-card at the right-most part of the query (now gro.aidepikiw@%), which the index on reverse(email_address) can satisfy.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] When the wildcard characters are used on both sides of the search word as *%wikipedia.org%*, the index available on this field is not used.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Rather only a sequential search is performed, which takes ⁠ $O(N)$ ⁠ time.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] To mitigate this, a full-text indexing approach can be used.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] A bitmap index is a special kind of indexing that stores the bulk of its data as bit arrays (bitmaps) and answers most queries by performing bitwise logical operations on these bitmaps.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] The most commonly used indexes, such as B+ trees, are most efficient if the values they index do not repeat or repeat a small number of times.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] In contrast, the bitmap index is designed for cases where the values of a variable repeat very frequently.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] For example, the sex field in a customer database usually contains at most three distinct values: male, female or unknown (not recorded).
[src:materialized-view/database-index] For such variables, the bitmap index can have a significant performance advantage over the commonly used trees.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] A dense index in databases is a file with pairs of keys and pointers for every record in the data file.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Every key in this file is associated with a particular pointer to *a record* in the sorted data file.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] In clustered indices with duplicate keys, the dense index points *to the first record* with that key.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] A sparse index in databases is a file with pairs of keys and pointers for every block in the data file.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Every key in this file is associated with a particular pointer *to the block* in the sorted data file.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] In clustered indices with duplicate keys, the sparse index points *to the lowest search key* in each block.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] A reverse-key index reverses the key value before entering it in the index.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Reversing the key value is particularly useful for indexing data such as sequence numbers, where new key values monotonically increase.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] An inverted index maps a content word to the document containing it, thereby allowing full-text searches.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] The primary index contains the key fields of the table and a pointer to the non-key fields of the table.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] The primary index is created automatically when the table is created in the database.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] It is used to index fields that are neither ordering fields nor key fields (there is no assurance that the file is organized on key field or primary key field).
[src:materialized-view/database-index] One index entry for every tuple in the data file (dense index) contains the value of the indexed attribute and pointer to the block or record.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Another type of index used in database systems is linear hashing.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Indices can be implemented using a variety of data structures.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Popular indices include balanced trees, B+ trees and hashes.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] In Microsoft SQL Server, the leaf node of the clustered index corresponds to the actual data, not simply a pointer to data that resides elsewhere, as is the case with a non-clustered index.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Each relation can have a single clustered index and many unclustered indices.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] An index is typically being accessed concurrently by several transactions and processes, and thus needs concurrency control.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] While in principle indexes can utilize the common database concurrency control methods, specialized concurrency control methods for indexes exist, which are applied in conjunction with the common methods for a substantial performance gain.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] In most cases, an index is used to quickly locate the data records from which the required data is read.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] In other words, the index is only used to locate data records in the table and not to return data.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] A covering index is a special case where the index itself contains the required data fields and can answer the required data.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] To find the Name for ID 13, an index on (ID) is useful, but the record must still be read to get the Name.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] However, an index on (ID, Name) contains the required data field and eliminates the need to look up the record.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Covering indexes are each for a specific table.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Queries which JOIN/ access across multiple tables, may potentially consider covering indexes on more than one of these tables.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] A covering index can dramatically speed up data retrieval but may itself be large due to the additional keys, which slow down data insertion and update.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] To reduce such index size, some systems allow including non-key fields in the index.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Non-key fields are not themselves part of the index ordering but only included at the leaf level, allowing for a covering index with less overall index size.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] This can be done in SQL with `CREATE INDEX my_index ON my_table (id) INCLUDE (name);`.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] No standard defines how to create indexes, because the ISO SQL Standard does not cover physical aspects.
[src:materialized-view/database-index] Indexes are one of the physical parts of database conception among others like storage (tablespace or filegroups).
[src:materialized-view/database-index] RDBMS vendors all give a `CREATE INDEX` syntax with some specific options that depend on their software's capabilities.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] In computing, a **materialized view** is a database object that contains the results of a query.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] For example, it may be a local copy of data located remotely, or may be a subset of the rows and/or columns of a table or join result, or may be a summary using an aggregate function.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] The process of setting up a materialized view is sometimes called **materialization**.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] This is a form of caching the results of a query, similar to memoization of the value of a function in functional languages, and it is sometimes described as a form of precomputation.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] As with other forms of precomputation, database users typically use materialized views for performance reasons, i.e. as a form of optimization.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] Materialized views that store data based on remote tables were also known as snapshots (deprecated Oracle terminology).
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] In any database management system following the relational model, a view is a virtual table representing the result of a database query.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] Whenever a query or an update addresses an ordinary view's virtual table, the DBMS converts these into queries or updates against the underlying base tables.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] A materialized view takes a different approach: the query result is cached as a concrete ("materialized") table (rather than a view as such) that may be updated from the original base tables from time to time.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] This enables much more efficient access, at the cost of extra storage and of some data being potentially out-of-date.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] Materialized views find use especially in data warehousing scenarios, where frequent queries of the actual base tables can be expensive.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] In a materialized view, indexes can be built on any column.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] In contrast, in a normal view, it's typically only possible to exploit indexes on columns that come directly from (or have a mapping to) indexed columns in the base tables; often this functionality is not offered at all.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] Materialized views were implemented first by the Oracle Database: the Query rewrite feature was added from version 8i.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] In PostgreSQL, version 9.3 and newer natively support materialized views.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] In version 9.3, a materialized view is not auto-refreshed, and is populated only at time of creation (unless `WITH NO DATA` is used).
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] It may be refreshed later manually using `REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW`.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] In version 9.4, the refresh may be concurrent with selects on the materialized view if `CONCURRENTLY` is used.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] Microsoft SQL Server differs from other RDBMS by the way of implementing materialized view via a concept known as "Indexed Views".
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] The main difference is that such views do not require a refresh because they are in fact always synchronized to the original data of the tables that compound the view.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] To achieve this, it is necessary that the lines of origin and destination are "deterministic" in their mapping, which limits the types of possible queries to do this.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] This mechanism has been realised since the 2000 version of SQL Server.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] Apache Kafka (since v0.10.2), Apache Spark (since v2.0), Apache Flink, Kinetica DB, Materialize, RisingWave, and Epsio all support materialized views on streams of data.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] Materialized views are also supported in Sybase SQL Anywhere.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] In IBM Db2, they are called "materialized query tables".
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] ClickHouse supports materialized views that automatically refresh on merges.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] MySQL doesn't support materialized views natively, but workarounds can be implemented by using triggers or stored procedures or by using the open-source application Flexviews.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] Materialized views can be implemented in Amazon DynamoDB using data modification events captured by DynamoDB Streams.
[src:materialized-view/materialized-view] Google announced in 8 April 2020 the availability of materialized views for BigQuery as a beta release.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] In computing, **online analytical processing (OLAP)** (/ˈoʊlæp/), is an approach to quickly answer multi-dimensional analytical (MDA) queries.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The term *OLAP* was created as a slight modification of the traditional database term online transaction processing (OLTP).
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is part of the broader category of business intelligence, which also encompasses relational databases, report writing and data mining.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Typical applications of OLAP include business reporting for sales, marketing, management reporting, business process management (BPM), budgeting and forecasting, financial reporting and similar areas, with new applications emerging, such as agriculture.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] OLAP tools enable users to analyse multidimensional data interactively from multiple perspectives.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] OLAP consists of three basic analytical operations: consolidation (roll-up), drill-down, and slicing and dicing.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Consolidation involves the aggregation of data that can be accumulated and computed in one or more dimensions.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] For example, all sales offices are rolled up to the sales department or sales division to anticipate sales trends.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] By contrast, the drill-down is a technique that allows users to navigate through the details.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] For instance, users can view the sales by individual products that make up a region's sales.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Slicing and dicing is a feature whereby users can take out (slicing) a specific set of data of the OLAP cube and view (dicing) the slices from different viewpoints.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] These viewpoints are sometimes called dimensions (such as looking at the same sales by salesperson, or by date, or by customer, or by product, or by region, etc.).
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Databases configured for OLAP use a multidimensional data model, allowing for complex analytical and ad hoc queries with a rapid execution time.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] They borrow aspects of navigational databases, hierarchical databases and relational databases.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is typically contrasted to OLTP (online transaction processing), which is generally characterized by much less complex queries, in a larger volume, to process transactions rather than for the purpose of business intelligence or reporting.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Whereas OLAP systems are mostly optimized for read, OLTP has to process all kinds of queries (read, insert, update and delete).
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] At the core of any OLAP system is an OLAP cube (also called a 'multidimensional cube' or a hypercube).
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] It consists of numeric facts called *measures* that are categorized by *dimensions*.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The measures are placed at the intersections of the hypercube, which is spanned by the dimensions as a vector space.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The usual interface to manipulate an OLAP cube is a matrix interface, like Pivot tables in a spreadsheet program, which performs projection operations along the dimensions, such as aggregation or averaging.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The cube metadata is typically created from a star schema or snowflake schema or fact constellation of tables in a relational database.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Measures are derived from the records in the fact table and dimensions are derived from the dimension tables.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Each *measure* can be thought of as having a set of *labels*, or meta-data associated with it.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] A *dimension* is what describes these *labels*; it provides information about the *measure*.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] A simple example would be a cube that contains a store's sales as a *measure*, and Date/Time as a *dimension*.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Each Sale has a Date/Time *label* that describes more about that sale.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is defined as "a variation of the relational model that uses multidimensional structures to organize data and express the relationships between data".
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The structure is broken into cubes and the cubes are able to store and access data within the confines of each cube.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] "Each cell within a multidimensional structure contains aggregated data related to elements along each of its dimensions".
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Even when data is manipulated it remains easy to access and continues to constitute a compact database format.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is quite popular for analytical databases that use online analytical processing (OLAP) applications.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Analytical databases use these databases because of their ability to deliver answers to complex business queries swiftly.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Data can be viewed from different angles, which gives a broader perspective of a problem unlike other models.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] It has been claimed that for complex queries OLAP cubes can produce an answer in around 0.1% of the time required for the same query on OLTP relational data.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The most important mechanism in OLAP which allows it to achieve such performance is the use of *aggregations*.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Aggregations are built from the fact table by changing the granularity on specific dimensions and aggregating up data along these dimensions, using an aggregate function (or *aggregation function*).
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The number of possible aggregations is determined by every possible combination of dimension granularities.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The combination of all possible aggregations and the base data contains the answers to every query which can be answered from the data.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Because usually there are many aggregations that can be calculated, often only a predetermined number are fully calculated; the remainder are solved on demand.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The problem of deciding which aggregations (views) to calculate is known as the view selection problem.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] View selection can be constrained by the total size of the selected set of aggregations, the time to update them from changes in the base data, or both.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The objective of view selection is typically to minimize the average time to answer OLAP queries, although some studies also minimize the update time.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Many approaches to the problem have been explored, including greedy algorithms, randomized search, genetic algorithms and A* search algorithm.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Some aggregation functions can be computed for the entire OLAP cube by precomputing values for each cell, and then computing the aggregation for a roll-up of cells by aggregating these aggregates, applying a divide and conquer algorithm to the multidimensional problem to compute them efficiently.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] For example, the overall sum of a roll-up is just the sum of the sub-sums in each cell.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Functions that can be decomposed in this way are called decomposable aggregation functions, and include `COUNT`, `MAX`, `MIN`, and `SUM`, which can be computed for each cell and then directly aggregated; these are known as self-decomposable aggregation functions.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] In other cases, the aggregate function cannot be computed without analyzing the entire set at once, though in some cases approximations can be computed; examples include `DISTINCT COUNT`, `MEDIAN`, and `MODE`; for example, the median of a set is not the median of medians of subsets.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] These latter are difficult to implement efficiently in OLAP, as they require computing the aggregate function on the base data, either computing them online (slow) or precomputing them for possible rollouts (large space).
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] OLAP systems have been traditionally categorized using the following taxonomy.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP (multi-dimensional online analytical processing) is the classic form of OLAP and is sometimes referred to as just OLAP.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP stores this data in an optimized multi-dimensional array storage, rather than in a relational database.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Some MOLAP tools require the pre-computation and storage of derived data, such as consolidations – the operation known as processing.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Such MOLAP tools generally utilize a pre-calculated data set referred to as a data cube.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The data cube contains all the possible answers to a given range of questions.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] As a result, they have a very fast response to queries.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] On the other hand, updating can take a long time depending on the degree of pre-computation.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Pre-computation can also lead to what is known as data explosion.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Other MOLAP tools, particularly those that implement the functional database model do not pre-compute derived data but make all calculations on demand other than those that were previously requested and stored in a cache.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Examples of commercial products that use MOLAP are Cognos Powerplay, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy, Microsoft Analysis Services, Essbase, TM1, Jedox, and icCube.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] While ROLAP uses a relational database source, generally the database must be carefully designed for ROLAP use.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] A database which was designed for OLTP will not function well as a ROLAP database.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Therefore, ROLAP still involves creating an additional copy of the data.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] However, since it is a database, a variety of technologies can be used to populate the database.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] In the OLAP industry ROLAP is usually perceived as being able to scale for large data volumes but suffering from slower query performance as opposed to MOLAP.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP Survey, the largest independent survey across all major OLAP products, being conducted for 6 years (2001 to 2006) have consistently found that companies using ROLAP report slower performance than those using MOLAP even when data volumes were taken into consideration.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] However, as with any survey there are a number of subtle issues that must be taken into account when interpreting the results.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Some companies select ROLAP because they intend to re-use existing relational database tables—these tables will frequently not be optimally designed for OLAP use.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The superior flexibility of ROLAP tools allows this less-than-optimal design to work, but performance suffers.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP tools in contrast would force the data to be re-loaded into an optimal OLAP design.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The undesirable trade-off between additional ETL cost and slow query performance has ensured that most commercial OLAP tools now use a "Hybrid OLAP" (HOLAP) approach, which allows the model designer to decide which portion of the data will be stored in MOLAP and which portion in ROLAP.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] There is no clear agreement across the industry as to what constitutes "Hybrid OLAP", except that a database will divide data between relational and specialized storage.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] For example, for some vendors, a HOLAP database will use relational tables to hold the larger quantities of detailed data and use specialized storage for at least some aspects of the smaller quantities of more-aggregate or less-detailed data.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP addresses the shortcomings of MOLAP and ROLAP by combining the capabilities of both approaches.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP tools can utilize both pre-calculated cubes and relational data sources.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores *aggregations* in MOLAP for fast query performance, and detailed data in ROLAP to optimize time of cube *processing*.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores some slice of data, usually the more recent one (i.e. sliced by Time dimension) in MOLAP for fast query performance, and older data in ROLAP.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Moreover, we can store some dices in MOLAP and others in ROLAP, leveraging the fact that in a large cuboid, there will be dense and sparse subregions.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The first product to provide HOLAP storage was Holos, but the technology also became available in other commercial products such as Microsoft Analysis Services, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy and SAP AG BI Accelerator.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The hybrid OLAP approach combines ROLAP and MOLAP technology, benefiting from the greater scalability of ROLAP and the faster computation of MOLAP.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] For example, a HOLAP server may store large volumes of detailed data in a relational database, while aggregations are kept in a separate MOLAP store.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Each type has certain benefits, although there is disagreement about the specifics of the benefits between providers.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Unlike relational databases, which had SQL as the standard query language, and widespread APIs such as ODBC, JDBC and OLEDB, there was no such unification in the OLAP world for a long time.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The first real standard API was OLE DB for OLAP specification from Microsoft which appeared in 1997 and introduced the MDX query language.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Several OLAP vendors – both server and client – adopted it.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] In 2001 Microsoft and Hyperion announced the XML for Analysis specification, which was endorsed by most of the OLAP vendors.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Since this also used MDX as a query language, MDX became the de facto standard.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Since September-2011 LINQ can be used to query SSAS OLAP cubes from Microsoft .NET.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The first product that performed OLAP queries was *Express,* which was released in 1970 (and acquired by Oracle in 1995 from Information Resources).
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] However, the term did not appear until 1993 when it was coined by Edgar F.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Codd, who has been described as "the father of the relational database".
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Codd's paper resulted from a short consulting assignment which Codd undertook for former Arbor Software (later Hyperion Solutions, and in 2007 acquired by Oracle), as a sort of marketing coup.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The company had released its own OLAP product, *Essbase*, a year earlier.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] As a result, Codd's "twelve laws of online analytical processing" were explicit in their reference to Essbase.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] There was some ensuing controversy and when Computerworld learned that Codd was paid by Arbor, it retracted the article.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP market experienced strong growth in the late 1990s with dozens of commercial products going into market.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] In 1998, Microsoft released its first OLAP Server – Microsoft Analysis Services, which drove wide adoption of OLAP technology and moved it into the mainstream.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] OLAP clients include many spreadsheet programs like Excel, web application, SQL, dashboard tools, etc.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Many clients support interactive data exploration where users select dimensions and measures of interest.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Some dimensions are used as filters (for slicing and dicing the data) while others are selected as the axes of a pivot table or pivot chart.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Users can also vary aggregation level (for drilling-down or rolling-up) the displayed view.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Clients can also offer a variety of graphical widgets such as sliders, geographic maps, heat maps and more which can be grouped and coordinated as dashboards.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] An extensive list of clients appears in the visualization column of the comparison of OLAP servers table.
[src:materialized-view/online-analytical-processing] Below is a list of top OLAP vendors in 2006, with figures in millions of US Dollars.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Generally, the query optimizer cannot be accessed directly by users: once queries are submitted to the database server, and parsed by the parser, they are then passed to the query optimizer where optimization occurs.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] However, some database engines allow guiding the query optimizer with hints.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] A query is a request for information from a database.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Since database structures are complex, in most cases, and especially for not-very-simple queries, the needed data for a query can be collected from a database by accessing it in different ways, through different data-structures, and in different orders.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Each different way typically requires different processing time.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Processing times of the same query may have large variance, from a fraction of a second to hours, depending on the chosen method.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] The purpose of query optimization, which is an automated process, is to find the way to process a given query in minimum time.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] The large possible variance in time justifies performing query optimization, though finding the exact optimal query plan, among all possibilities, is typically very complex, time-consuming by itself, may be too costly, and often practically impossible.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Thus query optimization typically tries to approximate the optimum by comparing several common-sense alternatives to provide in a reasonable time a "good enough" plan which typically does not deviate much from the best possible result.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] There is a trade-off between the amount of time spent figuring out the best query plan and the quality of the choice; the optimizer may not choose the best answer on its own.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Different qualities of database management systems have different ways of balancing these two.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Cost-based query optimizers evaluate the resource footprint of various query plans and use this as the basis for plan selection.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] These assign an estimated "cost" to each possible query plan, and choose the plan with the smallest cost.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Costs are used to estimate the runtime cost of evaluating the query, in terms of the number of I/O operations required, CPU path length, amount of disk buffer space, disk storage service time, and interconnect usage between units of parallelism, and other factors determined from the data dictionary.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] The set of query plans examined is formed by examining the possible access paths (e.g., primary index access, secondary index access, full file scan) and various relational table join techniques (e.g., merge join, hash join, product join).
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] The search space can become quite large depending on the complexity of the SQL query.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] These consist of logical optimization—which generates a sequence of relational algebra to solve the query—and physical optimization—which is used to determine the means of carrying out each operation.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Most query optimizers represent query plans as a tree of "plan nodes".
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] A plan node encapsulates a single operation that is required to execute the query.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] The nodes are arranged as a tree, in which intermediate results flow from the bottom of the tree to the top.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Each node has zero or more child nodes—those are nodes whose output is fed as input to the parent node.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] For example, a join node will have two child nodes, which represent the two join operands, whereas a sort node would have a single child node (the input to be sorted).
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] The leaves of the tree are nodes which produce results by scanning the disk, for example by performing an index scan or a sequential scan.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] The performance of a query plan is determined largely by the order in which the tables are joined.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] For example, when joining 3 tables A, B, C of size 10 rows, 10,000 rows, and 1,000,000 rows, respectively, a query plan that joins B and C first can take several orders-of-magnitude more time to execute than one that joins A and C first.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Most query optimizers determine join order via a dynamic programming algorithm pioneered by IBM's System R database project .
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] The optimizer then considers combining each pair of relations for which a join condition exists.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] For each pair, the optimizer will consider the available join algorithms implemented by the DBMS.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] It will preserve the cheapest way to join each pair of relations, in addition to the cheapest way to join each pair of relations that produces its output according to a particular sort order.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Then all three-relation query plans are computed, by joining each two-relation plan produced by the previous phase with the remaining relations in the query.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Sort order can avoid a redundant sort operation later on in processing the query.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Second, a particular sort order can speed up a subsequent join because it clusters the data in a particular way.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] A SQL query to a modern relational DBMS does more than just selections and joins.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] In particular, SQL queries often nest several layers of SPJ blocks (Select-Project-Join), by means of group by, exists, and not exists operators.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] In some cases such nested SQL queries can be flattened into a select-project-join query, but not always.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Query plans for nested SQL queries can also be chosen using the same dynamic programming algorithm as used for join ordering, but this can lead to an enormous escalation in query optimization time.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] So some database management systems use an alternative rule-based approach that uses a query graph model.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] One of the hardest problems in query optimization is to accurately estimate the costs of alternative query plans.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Optimizers cost query plans using a mathematical model of query execution costs that relies heavily on estimates of the cardinality, or number of tuples, flowing through each edge in a query plan.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Cardinality estimation in turn depends on estimates of the selection factor of predicates in the query.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Traditionally, database systems estimate selectivities through fairly detailed statistics on the distribution of values in each column, such as histograms.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] This technique works well for estimation of selectivities of individual predicates.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] However many queries have conjunctions of predicates such as `select count(*) from R where R.make='Honda' and R.model='Accord'`.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Query predicates are often highly correlated (for example, `model='Accord'` implies `make='Honda'`), and it is very hard to estimate the selectivity of the conjunct in general.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Poor cardinality estimates and uncaught correlation are one of the main reasons why query optimizers pick poor query plans.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] This is one reason why a database administrator should regularly update the database statistics, especially after major data loads/unloads.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Classical query optimization assumes that query plans are compared according to one single cost metric, usually execution time, and that the cost of each query plan can be calculated without uncertainty.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Both assumptions are sometimes violated in practice and multiple extensions of classical query optimization have been studied in the research literature that overcome those limitations.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Those extended problem variants differ in how they model the cost of single query plans and in terms of their optimization goal.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Classical query optimization associates each query plan with one scalar cost value.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Parametric query optimization assumes that query plan cost depends on parameters whose values are unknown at optimization time.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Such parameters can for instance represent the selectivity of query predicates that are not fully specified at optimization time but will be provided at execution time.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Parametric query optimization therefore associates each query plan with a cost function that maps from a multi-dimensional parameter space to a one-dimensional cost space.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] The goal of optimization is usually to generate all query plans that could be optimal for any of the possible parameter value combinations.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] This yields a set of relevant query plans.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] At run time, the best plan is selected out of that set once the true parameter values become known.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] The advantage of parametric query optimization is that optimization (which is in general a very expensive operation) is avoided at run time.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] There are often other cost metrics in addition to execution time that are relevant to compare query plans.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] In a cloud computing scenario for instance, one should compare query plans not only in terms of how much time they take to execute but also in terms of how much money their execution costs.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Or in the context of approximate query optimization, it is possible to execute query plans on randomly selected samples of the input data in order to obtain approximate results with reduced execution overhead.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] In such cases, alternative query plans must be compared in terms of their execution time but also in terms of the precision or reliability of the data they generate.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Multi-objective query optimization models the cost of a query plan as a cost vector where each vector component represents cost according to a different cost metric.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Classical query optimization can be considered as a special case of multi-objective query optimization where the dimension of the cost space (i.e., the number of cost vector components) is one.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Different cost metrics might conflict with each other (e.g., there might be one plan with minimal execution time and a different plan with minimal monetary execution fees in a cloud computing scenario).
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Therefore, the goal of optimization cannot be to find a query plan that minimizes all cost metrics but must be to find a query plan that realizes the best compromise between different cost metrics.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] What the best compromise is depends on user preferences (e.g., some users might prefer a cheaper plan while others prefer a faster plan in a cloud scenario).
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Multi-objective parametric query optimization generalizes parametric and multi-objective query optimization.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Plans are compared according to multiple cost metrics and plan costs may depend on parameters whose values are unknown at optimization time.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] The cost of a query plan is therefore modeled as a function from a multi-dimensional parameter space to a multi-dimensional cost space.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] The goal of optimization is to generate the set of query plans that can be optimal for each possible combination of parameter values and user preferences.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] A number of tools display query execution plans to show which operations have the highest processing cost.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Microsoft SMS, ApexSQLPlan, Hana, and Tableau are some examples.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] Fixing these issues found in these plans can shave tens of percent execution time, and in some cases can cut two-dimensional searches to linear ones.
[src:materialized-view/query-optimization] One of the primary and simplest optimization checklists is to use operations that most RDMS are designed to execute efficiently.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] A **query plan** (or **query execution plan**) is a sequence of steps used to access data in a SQL relational database management system.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] This is a specific case of the relational model concept of access plans.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] Since SQL is declarative, there are typically many alternative ways to execute a given query, with widely varying performance.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] When a query is submitted to the database, the query optimizer evaluates some of the different, correct possible plans for executing the query and returns what it considers the best option.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] Because query optimizers are imperfect, database users and administrators sometimes need to manually examine and tune the plans produced by the optimizer to get better performance.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] A given database management system may offer one or more mechanisms for returning the plan for a given query.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] Some packages feature tools which will generate a graphical representation of a query plan.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] Other tools allow a special mode to be set on the connection to cause the DBMS to return a textual description of the query plan.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] Another mechanism for retrieving the query plan involves querying a virtual database table after executing the query to be examined.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] In Oracle, for instance, this can be achieved using the EXPLAIN PLAN statement.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] The UI allows exploration of various attributes of the operators involved in the query plan, including the operator type, the number of rows each operator consumes or produces, and the expected cost of each operator's work.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] It indicates that the query engine will do a scan over the primary key index on the Employee table and a matching seek through the primary key index (the ContactID column) on the Contact table to find matching rows.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] The resulting rows from each side will be shown to a nested loops join operator, sorted, then returned as the result set to the connection.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] In order to tune the query, the user must understand the different operators that the database may use, and which ones might be more efficient than others while still providing semantically correct query results.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] Reviewing the query plan can present opportunities for new indexes or changes to existing indexes.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] It can also show that the database is not properly taking advantage of existing indexes (see query optimizer).
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] A query optimizer will not always choose the most efficient query plan for a given query.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] In some databases the query plan can be reviewed, problems found, and then the query optimizer gives hints on how to improve it.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] In other databases, alternatives to express the same query (other queries that return the same results) can be tried.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] Some query tools can generate embedded hints in the query, for use by the optimizer.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] Some databases - like Oracle - provide a **plan table** for query tuning.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] This plan table will return the cost and time for executing a query.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] For CBO to be used, all the tables referenced by the query must be analyzed.
[src:materialized-view/query-plan] To analyze a table, a DBA can launch code from the DBMS_STATS package.
[src:materialized-view/rules-materializedviews] Materialized views in PostgreSQL use the rule system like views do, but persist the results in a table-like form.
[src:materialized-view/rules-materializedviews] The information about a materialized view in the PostgreSQL system catalogs is exactly the same as it is for a table or view.
[src:materialized-view/rules-materializedviews] So for the parser, a materialized view is a relation, just like a table or a view.
[src:materialized-view/rules-materializedviews] When a materialized view is referenced in a query, the data is returned directly from the materialized view, like from a table; the rule is only used for populating the materialized view.
[src:materialized-view/rules-materializedviews] While access to the data stored in a materialized view is often much faster than accessing the underlying tables directly or through a view, the data is not always current; yet sometimes current data is not needed.
[src:materialized-view/rules-materializedviews] This materialized view might be useful for displaying a graph in the dashboard created for salespeople.
[src:materialized-view/rules-materializedviews] Another use for a materialized view is to allow faster access to data brought across from a remote system through a foreign data wrapper.
[src:materialized-view/rules-materializedviews] A simple example using `file_fdw` is below, with timings, but since this is using cache on the local system the performance difference compared to access to a remote system would usually be greater than shown here.
[src:materialized-view/rules-materializedviews] Notice we are also exploiting the ability to put an index on the materialized view, whereas `file_fdw` does not support indexes; this advantage might not apply for other sorts of foreign data access.
[src:materialized-view/rules-materializedviews] Either way, the word is spelled wrong, so let's look for what we might have wanted.
[src:materialized-view/rules-materializedviews] If you can tolerate periodic update of the remote data to the local database, the performance benefit can be substantial.
[src:materialized-view/rules-materializedviews] If you see anything in the documentation that is not correct, does not match your experience with the particular feature or requires further clarification, please use this form to report a documentation issue.
